<title>Paper Scout Research Report - 2026-06-10</title>

<callout emoji="✅" background-color="light-green">
  <p><b>Standout:</b> QGF (Zhou et al., 2026) is the clearest seed for a research thread. It shows that test-time gradient guidance can match training-time RL for flow policies, sidestepping the instability that has plagued actor-critic training of diffusion and flow models. Combined with OASIS, AHA-WAM, and TBD-VLA, this run paints a coherent picture: generative action models are maturing, and the frontier is shifting from <em>how to train them</em> to <em>how to guide, decouple, and deploy them efficiently.</em></p>
</callout>

<p>This run scouts papers from 2026-06-08 to 2026-06-10 and follows four strong threads. Three share a central technology — flow matching or diffusion for robot action generation — but attack different bottlenecks: data scarcity (OASIS), inference latency (AHA-WAM), action decoding architecture (TBD-VLA), and policy optimization without retraining (QGF). A fourth paper, the TBD-VLA architecture, rounds out the picture by showing how discrete diffusion can be temporally structured inside a VLA. Together they suggest that the next leap in robot control will come not from scaling policy parameters, but from smarter training pipelines, asynchronous inference, and test-time compute.</p>

<h1>Simulation-to-Reality for Humanoid Loco-Manipulation</h1>

<p>Humanoid robots are finally leaving the lab, but data remains the binding constraint. Real-robot teleoperation is accurate yet painfully slow; simulation is fast but historically struggled to transfer. Two papers this period attack the data bottleneck from opposite directions: OASIS by making simulation the primary data source, and a shortlist of benchmarks (SpatialWorld, WorldOlympiad) by making evaluation more realistic.</p>

