<h2>OASIS: From Simulation Data Collection to Real-World Humanoid Loco-Manipulation</h2>

<p>Zehao Yu et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.08548">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.08548">PDF</a> · <a href="https://oasis-humanoid.github.io/">Project</a></p>

<p>OASIS is a complete pipeline that learns humanoid loco-manipulation policies entirely from simulation data. The core insight is practical: separate the <em>cost</em> of teleoperation from the <em>size</em> of the resulting dataset by collecting trajectories in lightweight real-time rendering, then replaying them offline under diverse photorealistic conditions.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:oasis:overview]]</p>

<p>The pipeline has four stages. First, real-world object photos are fed to Hunyuan3D for mesh generation and Qwen3-VL for physical dimension and material estimation. Second, a human operator teleoperates a simulated Unitree G1 via VR (PICO 4U) in Isaac-Sim's real-time mode. Third, the recorded state trajectories are replayed and rendered under randomized textures, lighting, and camera extrinsics — turning one demonstration into twenty. Fourth, a hierarchical policy learns: a high-level Flow Matching planner predicts 32-frame whole-body reference motion chunks from CLIP text, DINOv2 vision, and proprioception; a low-level Teleopit controller tracks them at 50 Hz.</p>

<p>The method is mechanically sound. The reference motion command <latex>m_t \in \mathbb{R}^{67}</latex> compactly encodes root pose deltas, joint positions, and joint increments (Eq. 1 in the paper). Flow matching trains the denoiser to regress the constant-velocity field between noise and data:</p>

<pre lang="python" caption="Flow matching objective (reconstructed)"><code>loss = MSE(denoiser(a_tau, tau, condition), noise - action_chunk)
a_tau = (1 - tau) * action_chunk + tau * noise</code></pre>

<p>What makes OASIS stand out is not any single algorithmic novelty — 3D generation, VLM attribute estimation, and flow matching are all existing pieces — but the <em>system integration</em> into a scalable humanoid data pipeline. The two-stage decoupled rendering is a genuine scaling insight: operator time is linear in trajectories, while dataset size is linear in renderings, and the gap between them is whatever compute you can afford.</p>

<p>Does it work? The real-robot experiments say yes, with caveats. Under a 50-trajectory budget per task, simulation-only training matches or exceeds real-robot training on most tasks, and an equal mix outperforms both. The ablations confirm that <b>lighting randomization dominates transfer</b>: disabling it causes near-total failure, while texture and camera randomization matter less. A curriculum-based rollout mechanism (progressively replacing ground-truth history with the model's own predictions during training) is critical — without it, success rates collapse from 7–10/10 to 0–2/10.</p>

<p>But the evidence has limits. The evaluation is small: 10 trials × 4 tasks on one robot, with no error bars. Asset dimension errors reach 3 cm (~12% relative) and mass is assigned via uniform-density category lookup, which the authors themselves flag as a weakness for contact-rich tasks. Camera randomization is narrow (±1 cm position, ±1.5° rotation) — far less aggressive than VIRAL's multi-camera training. And <b>no code is public</b> as of this writing, so independent verification is impossible. The project page links to nothing but the paper and a video.</p>

<p>The comparison with related methods is instructive:</p>

