<p>OASIS's niche is clear: it is the first to apply the MimicGen-style "teleop + replay + rendering" paradigm to <em>whole-body humanoid loco-manipulation</em>. MimicGen and DexMimicGen are fixed-base or upper-body only. Whether that generalizes to dynamic locomotion or contact-rich manipulation remains an open question.</p>

<h1>World-Action Models: Beyond Synchronous Prediction</h1>

<p>World-action models (WAMs) jointly learn visual scene dynamics and action generation, injecting physical priors into control. But existing WAMs force world prediction and action execution to share the same short horizon, making the video branch waste capacity on redundant adjacent-frame variations. AHA-WAM asks: what if the world planner thinks slowly and the action executor acts fast?</p>

<h2>AHA-WAM: Asynchronous Horizon-Adaptive World-Action Modeling</h2>

<p>Jisong Cai et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.09811">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.09811">PDF</a> · <a href="https://serene-sivy.github.io/aha-wam/">Project</a></p>

<p>AHA-WAM reorganizes world-action modeling around a temporal asymmetry. A <b>slow video DiT</b> (Wan2.2-5B, horizon <latex>h_v = 64</latex>) maintains rolling key-value memory over past observations and exposes reusable layerwise latent context. A <b>fast action DiT</b> (~1.02B params, horizon <latex>h_a = 16</latex>) executes short action chunks in closed loop by querying that context through layerwise joint attention. The video branch refreshes only periodically; the action branch runs at full control frequency.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:ahawam:architecture]]</p>

<p>The central technical challenge is <b>stale planner context</b>. If the video DiT only refreshes every few action chunks, the cached K/V context may misalign with the current scene. AHA-WAM solves this with <b>Observation-Guided Video-Context Routing (OVCR)</b>, a four-step mechanism that adapts cached planner context to the latest observation without rerunning the video DiT:</p>

<ol>
  <li><b>Routing queries</b> — 32 learnable base queries attend over the current visual observation tokens to produce compact, observation-conditioned slots.</li>
  <li><b>Planner read</b> — These queries attend to the cached planner K/V from the last refresh, retrieving chunk-relevant information.</li>
  <li><b>Residual update</b> — A lightweight layerwise router predicts residual K/V updates from the retrieved features.</li>
  <li><b>Gated merge</b> — A learned sigmoid gate blends the residuals into the cached context.</li>
</ol>

<p>The adapted context <latex>\widetilde{\mathcal{C}}_t^p</latex> is then consumed by the action DiT through layerwise joint attention (Eq. 3):</p>

<pre lang="python" caption="Layerwise joint attention (reconstructed)"><code>def forward_action_layer(action_q, action_k, action_v,
                         planner_k_adapted, planner_v_adapted):
    k = concat(action_k, planner_k_adapted)
    v = concat(action_v, planner_v_adapted)
    out = attention(action_q, k, v)
    return out</code></pre>

<p>To prevent the action expert from overfitting to a fixed planner-executor phase, <b>horizon-adaptive offset training</b> randomly shifts the action-chunk grid by <latex>\delta \sim \mathcal{U}\{0, \dots, h_a - 1\}</latex> within the planner horizon. This exposes the action DiT to all possible alignment offsets it will encounter during streaming deployment.</p>

<p>The ablations tell a clear story. Naive async execution (decoupling without adaptation) drops RoboTwin success by 3.2 points. Adding rolling K/V memory recovers 2.4 of those. Adding OVCR recovers the rest and pushes performance <em>above</em> the synchronous Fast-WAM baseline (+0.97 points). OVCR is the decisive ingredient.</p>

