<p>The inference stack is impressively engineered. TensorRT + CUDA Graphs + hot-path redundancy elimination cut action-chunk latency from 415 ms (PyTorch eager) to 41 ms (24.2 Hz). ODE distillation further reduces to 17.6 ms (56.9 Hz) with only a 2.6-point simulation accuracy drop. All latency numbers are measured on an RTX 5090D — a cutting-edge consumer GPU — so portability to datacenter or edge hardware is an open question.</p>

<p>Real-world evaluation is limited but promising: 78.3% success across 4 bimanual tasks on AgileX Piper arms, matching <latex>\pi_{0.5}</latex> (76.7%) without generalist pretraining. Only 4 tasks, ~120 episodes each, with RoboCOIN pretraining — so the "no pretraining" claim applies to simulation, not deployment. And like OASIS, <b>no code is public</b>. The project page is a glossy shell with no repository link.</p>

<h1>Generative Policies for Robot Control</h1>

<p>If OASIS and AHA-WAM ask "how do we get data and run models fast enough?", TBD-VLA and QGF ask "how do we make the action model itself better?" Both use generative modeling — discrete block diffusion and continuous flow matching, respectively — but attack orthogonal problems: TBD-VLA redesigns the decoding architecture for temporally coherent, low-latency action generation; QGF redesigns the optimization paradigm so the policy never needs unstable actor-critic training at all.</p>

<h2>TBD-VLA: Temporal Block Diffusion Vision Language Action Model</h2>

<p>Sung-Wook Lee et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.07895">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.07895">PDF</a> · <a href="https://tbd-vla.github.io/">Project</a></p>

<p>Discrete VLA models generate actions as tokens from a VLM backbone, but autoregressive decoding is too slow for closed-loop control, while fully parallel decoding sacrifices temporal structure. TBD-VLA splits the difference: it partitions action sequences into temporal blocks, performs <b>masked discrete diffusion within each block</b> (parallel), and maintains <b>autoregressive generation across blocks</b> (temporal). The result is a 2B-parameter Qwen3-VL model that achieves 97.7% average success on LIBERO — a modest 0.8-point margin over <latex>\pi_{0.5}</latex> — but with an architecture that enables a genuinely useful inference trick.</p>

<p>[[figure-anchor:tbdvla:overview]]</p>

<p>The training efficiency comes from a <b>doubled-layout attention mask</b>. Instead of running K separate forward passes (one per block), the input sequence is laid out as <code>[prefix] [clean_0] [noised_0] [clean_1] [noised_1] ...</code> with shared RoPE positions between clean and noised twins. A custom mask packs all block-level losses into one forward pass while preventing information leakage (the noised block cannot attend to its own clean twin). Our reconstruction verifies the mask shape and no-leak property.</p>

<p>The most practically interesting idea is <b>Real-Time Chunking (RTC)</b>. During closed-loop control, inference latency means the robot has no new actions for <latex>d</latex> timesteps. TBD-VLA handles this by <b>freezing the committed action tail</b> and reusing it as in-painting context for the next generation cycle. Because the model was trained with masked block diffusion — it routinely sees partial action context and must complete the block — this hard in-painting is natively aligned with the training objective. Without RTC, TBD-VLA collapses from 97.7% to 72.3% at latency <latex>L=4</latex>; with RTC it holds at 93.2%.</p>

<p><b>A critical reading:</b> the +20.9 pp RTC boost is vs. TBD-VLA <em>without</em> RTC, not vs. the baseline. The cross-method comparison against <latex>\pi_{0.5}</latex> with RTC is only +3.4 pp — still meaningful, but much smaller. The paper's phrasing could easily be misread.</p>

<p>Another striking result is <b>expectation sampling</b>: instead of taking the argmax token, TBD-VLA decodes each scalar action as a weighted average over bin centers using the full predicted distribution. This is worth <b>+7.1 points</b> over argmax on SimplerEnv Google Robot, suggesting the token distributions retain genuinely useful uncertainty that standard decoding discards.</p>

