<p>The block size ablation confirms <latex>m=4</latex> as a sweet spot: fully autoregressive is slower and worse; fully parallel is fastest but worst. The real-world evaluation is minimal (3 tasks, 50 demos each, FR3 robot) and the paper honestly reports a complete failure on liquid transfer under camera viewpoint shift. Like OASIS and AHA-WAM, <b>no code is public</b> — the project page is empty. The LeRobot framework is mentioned for training, but configs and model definitions are absent.</p>

<hr/>

<h2>QGF: Test-Time Gradient Guidance of Flow Policies in Reinforcement Learning</h2>

<p>Zhiyuan Zhou et al. (2026) · <a href="https://huggingface.co/papers/2606.11087">HF</a> · <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.11087">PDF</a> · <a href="https://github.com/zhouzypaul/qgf">Code</a></p>

<p>QGF is the standout of this run. It asks a radical question: instead of designing a more stable RL objective for flow policies, can we keep the actor training purely supervised and do <em>all</em> policy optimization at test time?</p>

<p>The idea is simple in concept but subtle in execution. Train a reference flow policy via standard behavioral cloning. Train a critic via IQL (in-sample, no policy interaction). At inference, guide each denoising step with the critic gradient. The challenge is <em>where</em> to evaluate that gradient. Three options exist:</p>

<ul>
  <li><b>OOD gradient</b> <latex>\nabla_{a_t} Q(s, a_t)</latex>: Evaluate at the noisy action. The critic has never seen noisy actions — gradient is biased and exploitative.</li>
  <li><b>BPTT gradient</b> <latex>\nabla_{a_t} Q(s, \text{ODE}(a_t))</latex>: Backprop through the full denoising chain. Expensive and high-variance.</li>
  <li><b>QGF gradient</b> <latex>\nabla_{\hat{a}_1} Q(s, \hat{a}_1)</latex> with <latex>\hat{a}_1 = a_t + (1-t) v_\theta(s, a_t, t)</latex>: Approximate the clean action with one large Euler step, evaluate the gradient there, and drop the Jacobian entirely.</li>
</ul>

<p>[[figure-anchor:qgf:probe]]</p>

<p>The QGF estimator is counter-intuitively <em>better</em> than its more exact cousins. Our 1D diagnostic probe reproduces the qualitative behavior of the paper's Figure 2: a tri-modal flow matching distribution guided by QGF shifts mass cleanly to the optimal mode, while OOD gets stuck at a suboptimal mode and BPTT shows high variance. The probe also confirms that including the exact Jacobian (QGF-Jacobian) <em>increases</em> gradient variance and hurts performance — a result that echoes the broader ML literature on approximate gradients (feedback alignment, synthetic gradients) but is still surprising.</p>

<p>Empirically, QGF outperforms all prior test-time methods (QFQL, BPTT, GradStep, CFGRL) and is competitive with the best training-time baseline (EDP) across 20 OGBench tasks with action chunking. It uses orders of magnitude less compute than best-of-N sampling: BFN(N=4) needs ~4× the FLOPs yet performs worse. QGF+BFN(N=4) matches BFN(N=16), showing that gradient guidance is a far cheaper form of test-time compute than rejection sampling.</p>

<p>The scaling story is positive but bounded. QGF improves from 800k to 3.2M parameters while QAM (a training-time baseline) flatlines. But both methods <b>overfit at 12.7M parameters</b>. The headline "scales with model size" only holds up to a point. And QGF cannot rescue a poorly trained base policy — an important practical caveat that the paper admits in its limitations section.</p>

<p>Unlike the other three papers in this run, <b>QGF's code is public and complete</b>. We cloned the repository, inspected the core inference loop in <code>agents/qgf.py</code>, and verified that the implementation matches Algorithm 1 exactly. The 1D probe is self-contained and runnable. This makes QGF the most buildable contribution of the period.</p>

<h1>Cross-cutting Observations</h1>

<p><b>Flow and diffusion have become the default action representation.</b> All four deep-dive papers use flow matching or diffusion for action generation: OASIS (Flow Matching planner), AHA-WAM (Flow Matching dual-DiT), TBD-VLA (discrete block diffusion), QGF (flow-matching policy). This is no longer a niche — it is the dominant paradigm for expressive robot policies. The open research question is shifting from "should we use diffusion?" to "how do we make it fast, structured, and optimizable?"</p>

<p><b>Code availability is the run's sharpest dividing line.</b> QGF ships a complete public repository. OASIS, AHA-WAM, and TBD-VLA have project pages with videos and figures but no source code. This pattern — strong empirical claims without reproducible artifacts — is becoming common in robotics, where training pipelines are complex and hardware-dependent. It is also a liability: without configs and model definitions, the community cannot verify ablations, reproduce baselines, or build follow-up work. The verifier on this run treated missing code as a blocker for deeper validation, not a reason to stop investigating, but the gap is real.</p>

<p><b>Test-time compute is emerging as a third axis of robot policy design.</b> Historically, the field has focused on training data and model architecture. QGF and TBD-VLA's RTC introduce a third dimension: how much compute to spend at inference to improve actions without retraining. QGF shows that gradient guidance can be as effective as actor-critic training; TBD-VLA shows that in-painting can recover from inference latency. Both suggest that for expensive VLA models, test-time optimization may be more practical than training-time RL.</p>

<p><b>Simulation data is crossing the credibility threshold for humanoids.</b> OASIS's claim that simulation-only training matches real-robot data on a Unitree G1, while limited in evaluation scale, aligns with VIRAL's earlier success and suggests a trend: for humanoid loco-manipulation, visual diversity from randomized rendering may matter more than physics fidelity. If this holds, the bottleneck shifts from "better simulators" to "better asset generation pipelines" — which is exactly what OASIS's Hunyuan3D + Qwen3-VL pipeline addresses.</p>

<p><b>Temporal structure in action generation is undervalued.</b> AHA-WAM decouples world and action temporal horizons. TBD-VLA introduces temporal blocks that preserve autoregressive structure across time while enabling parallel decoding within blocks. Both find that treating actions as an unstructured bag of tokens (fully parallel) or as rigidly sequential (fully autoregressive) is suboptimal. The middle ground — structured temporal blocks with intra-block parallelism — appears to be the sweet spot for both speed and coherence.</p>

<h1>What to Build Next</h1>

<ul>
  <li><b>Combine QGF with OASIS.</b> OASIS trains a Flow Matching policy on simulation data; QGF guides flow policies with critic gradients at test time. A natural next step is to train an IQL critic on OASIS's simulation data and deploy QGF guidance on the real robot, potentially improving over the base BC policy without any real-world retraining.</li>
  <li><b>Apply AHA-WAM's OVCR to TBD-VLA.</b> TBD-VLA's RTC handles inference latency by in-painting; AHA-WAM handles it by asynchronously refreshing planner context. A hybrid that uses block-diffusion action generation inside an async world-action framework could get the best of both architectures.</li>
  <li><b>Scale QGF to VLA backbones.</b> QGF is currently evaluated on small MLP flow policies (up to 12.7M params). Scaling the gradient estimator to 2B-parameter VLMs like TBD-VLA's Qwen3-VL backbone is an open and important challenge.</li>
</ul>

<p><i>Investigated 2026-06-10. Papers covered: 2606.08548, 2606.09811, 2606.07895, 2606.11087. Shortlisted: 2605.25077, 2606.06556, 2606.09669, 2606.11129, 2606.09828, 2606.07723, 2606.06476.</i></p>
